		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">INI file</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>The <b>INI file</b> <a href="/wiki/File_format" title="File format">format</a> is a <a href="/wiki/De_facto" title="De facto">de facto</a> standard for <a href="/wiki/Configuration_file" title="Configuration file">configuration files</a>. INI files are simple <a href="/wiki/Text_file" title="Text file">text files</a> with a <a href="#Format" title="">basic structure</a>. They are commonly associated with <a href="/wiki/Microsoft_Windows" title="Microsoft Windows">Microsoft Windows</a>, but are also used on other <a href="/wiki/Platform_(computing)" title="Platform (computing)" class="mw-redirect">platforms</a>. The use of the "INI file" has been deprecated in Windows and corresponding data should be placed in the registry. The name "INI file" comes from the <a href="/wiki/Filename_extension" title="Filename extension">filename extension</a> usually used, "<tt>.INI</tt>", that stands for "<b>ini</b>tialization". Sometimes, files using the INI file format will use a different extension, such as "<tt>.CFG</tt>", "<tt>.conf</tt>", or "<tt>.TXT</tt>".</p>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="clear: right; margin-bottom: .5em; float: right; padding: .5em 0 .8em 1.4em; background: none; width: auto;">
<tr>
<td>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
